A vote among ThyssenKrupp's 20,500 steelworkers saw 92.2 percent of them accept an agreement — struck just before Christmas — which foresees no forced layoffs or major site closures until September 30, 2026, Germany's metalworkers' union IG Metall announced on Monday. In September, ThyssenKrupp and India's Tata Steel unveiled plans to merge their European steel operations and forge Europe's second-largest steel group after ArcelorMittal, a move which has led to fears over significant job cuts. Read more: Duisburg plant epitomizes Europe's steel industry woes The two companies said the deal would help them to tackle overcapacity in Europe's steel market, which faces cheap imports — mainly from China — subdued construction demand and inefficient legacy plants. They have already announced 4,000 job cuts as part of the tie-up, with 2,000 steelworkers planned to be made redundant in Germany. Send  Facebook   Twitter   Google+   Whatsapp   
